"Walz A., Calonder G.-P., Hagedorn F., Lardelli C., Lundström C., Stöckli V.","Regional CO2 budget, countermeasures and reduction aims for the Alpine tourist region of Davos, Switzerland",2008,"Energy Policy","36","2",,"811","820",,,10.1016/j.enpol.2007.11.001,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-38049186736&partnerID=40&md5=6d9d0fc02f1b348f4612419cced8d1de","WSL, Swiss Federal Institute of Snow and Avalanche Research SLF, Flüelastrasse 11, CH-7260 Davos, Switzerland; Landschaft Davos Gemeinde, Umweltschutzamt, Rathaus, CH-7270 Davos, Switzerland; WSL, Swiss Federal Research Institute, Zürcherstrasse 111, CH-8903 Birmensdorf, Switzerland","Walz, A., WSL, Swiss Federal Institute of Snow and Avalanche Research SLF, Flüelastrasse 11, CH-7260 Davos, Switzerland; Calonder, G.-P., Landschaft Davos Gemeinde, Umweltschutzamt, Rathaus, CH-7270 Davos, Switzerland; Hagedorn, F., WSL, Swiss Federal Research Institute, Zürcherstrasse 111, CH-8903 Birmensdorf, Switzerland; Lardelli, C., WSL, Swiss Federal Institute of Snow and Avalanche Research SLF, Flüelastrasse 11, CH-7260 Davos, Switzerland; Lundström, C., WSL, Swiss Federal Institute of Snow and Avalanche Research SLF, Flüelastrasse 11, CH-7260 Davos, Switzerland; Stöckli, V., WSL, Swiss Federal Institute of Snow and Avalanche Research SLF, Flüelastrasse 11, CH-7260 Davos, Switzerland","In its latest report, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) concludes that global climate change can still be slowed down if greenhouse gas emissions are rapidly and strongly reduced. We present a detailed regional CO2 budget for the Alpine tourist region of Davos, Switzerland, including emissions and potential sinks. The aim of the study was (1) to estimate the most important CO2 sources and sinks, (2) to identify the most efficient reduction measures and (3) to assess the feasibility of different reduction targets. The results show that the emissions due to heating contribute to a proportion of 86.3% to the total budget, which is mainly due to the harsh local climate and the tourism-focused local economy. They also show that the yearly CO2 emissions per capita in Davos exceed the Swiss average of 6 tonnes by 25%. The augmentation of the carbon pool through the natural environment compares to 10.3% of the total emissions, and further afforestation of the community forest can contribute to an improvement of the total budget by 2.6%. The reduction aim of -15% until 2015 (compared with 2004), as set by the municipality itself, could be easily reached through better building insulation and the use of renewable energy sources. More ambitious aims, such as a 2000 W-society or CO2 neutrality, however, will not be realised without major drawbacks in living standards. © 2007 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Mountain region; Reduction measures; Regional CO2 budget","Carbon dioxide; Climate change; Emission control; Environmental impact; Gas emissions; Greenhouse gases; Renewable energy resources; Afforestation; Carbon pool; Tourism; Energy policy; carbon budget; carbon dioxide; carbon emission; climate change; global climate; greenhouse gas; Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change; mountain region; pollution control; Central Europe; Davos; Eurasia; Europe; Graubunden; Switzerland",,,,,,"Bebi, P., Kienast, F., Schönenberger, W., Assessing structures in mountain forests as a basis for investigating the forests' dynamics and protective function (2001) Forest Ecology and Management, 145, pp. 3-14; Bernoulli, M., Korner, C., Dry matter allocation in treeline trees (1999) Phyton-Annales Rei Botanicae, 39, pp. 7-11; Capaul, U., (2002) Ökobilanz-Bestandeserhebung 2000/01: Stand der Massnahmenumsetzung, , Stadt Schaffhausen, Schaffhausen; Dürrenberger, G., Hartmann, C., Regional energy and CO2 scenarios: a decision support tool for policy makers (2002) Environmental Impact Assessment Review, 22, pp. 449-461; Engesser, T., (2005) Emissionskataster 2004 der Stadt Winterthur, , Gesundheitsamt der Stadt Winterthur, Winterthur; Grubb, M., Vrolijk, C., Brack, D., (1999) The Kyoto Protocol: A Guide and Assessment, , Royal Institute of International Affairs, London; Jochem, E., R&D and innovation policy-preconditions for making steps towards a 2000 Watt/cap society (2004) Energy & Environment, 15 (2), pp. 283-296; Krewitt, W., Simon, S., Graus, W., Teske, S., Zervos, A., Schafer, O., The 2 °C scenario-a sustainable world energy perspective (2007) Energy Policy, 35, pp. 4969-4980; Lardelli, C., Bebi, P., Veränderung von Lawinenschutzwäldern in Davos (2005) Bündner Wald, 4, pp. 69-71; Lötscher, A., (2006) Personal communication based on recent observations of the Amt für Energie Graubünden and Lötscher, A., 1999. Statistische Auswertung der wärmetechnischen Qualität von bestehenden Wohnbauten im Kanton Graubünden, , Amt für Energie Graubünden, Chur; Perruchoud, D., Kienast, F., Kaufmann, E., Bräker, O.U., 20th century carbon budget of forest soils in the Alps (1999) Ecosystems, 2, pp. 320-337; Pohl, T., (2001) Treibhausgas Emissionsbilanz der Stadt Luzern 1990-1999, , Umweltschutz Stadt Luzern, Luzern; Schmid, S., Thürig, E., Kaufmann, E., Lischke, H., Bugmann, H., Effect of forest management on future carbon pools and fluxes: a model comparison (2006) Forest Ecology and Management, 237, pp. 65-82; (2006) Schweizerische Gesamtenergiestatistik 2005, , SFOE, Swiss Federal Office of Energy SFOE, Berne; Werner, F., Taverna, R., Hofer, P., Richter, K., Greenhouse gas dynamics of an increased use of wood in buildings in Switzerland (2006) Climatic Change, 74, pp. 319-347","Walz, A.; WSL, Swiss Federal Institute of Snow and Avalanche Research SLF, Flüelastrasse 11, CH-7260 Davos, Switzerland; email: walz@slf.ch",,,,,,,,03014215,,ENPYA,,"English","Energy Policy",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-38049186736
